This disqualification was quite obsolete under Justinian.

Among the enactments disabling certain classes from taking undera will either in whole or in part are the following :—

(1) By the lex lunia Norbana Latini Iuniani were prohibited from taking either as heirs or as legatees, unless they acquired the civitas within roo days, Gaius i. 23-4, ii. 110, 275, Ulpian‚ reg. 17. 1.

(2) By a lex lulia oi Augustus, the coelebs (unmarried person) could take nothing under the will oi one unrelated to him or her within the sixth degree as either heir or legatee, unless he or she married within roo days next alter hearing oi the right. Certain classes were excepted on account of age, physical incapacity, etc, Ulpian‚ reg. 14- 16 and 18.

(3) By the lex Papia Poppaea, five years later in date, the orbus (i. e. person who had been married but had no children living, Ulpian‚ reg. 16. 1) could take under wills ol persons outside the sixth degree onlya moiety oi what was given them. One child was sufficient to save a man lrom the statute, for ingenuae three, ior libertae four were required.
